The paper deals with network information theory, which is a subfield of information theory that has applications in computer science. The paper uses concentration inequalities and other mathematical tools to prove new mutual covering bounds, which are relevant to coding theorems and joint distribution simulation problems. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also involves combinatorial and probabilistic arguments, which suggest that it could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper uses a weighted sum trick and Talagrand's concentration inequality, which are techniques that are commonly used in machine learning and statistical inference, suggesting that it could also be relevant to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
